.SH GLOBAL FLAGS
Every subcommand accepts these universal flags (documented in
.BR lamboot-tools (7)):
.TP
.BR \-\-help ", " \-h
Show inline help
.TP
.B \-\-version
Print tool and toolkit version
.TP
.B \-\-json
Emit unified JSON output (schema v1)
.TP
.B \-\-json-schema
Print the JSON schema this tool emits
.TP
.BR \-\-verbose ", " \-v
Informational output beyond the default
.TP
.BR \-\-quiet ", " \-q
Only warnings and errors
.TP
.B \-\-no-color
Disable ANSI color (auto on non-TTY)
.TP
.B \-\-dry-run
Print planned actions without executing
.TP
.BR \-\-yes ", " \-y
Answer yes to interactive prompts
.TP
.B \-\-force
Skip safety checks (per-subcommand semantics)
.TP
.B \-\-auto
Non-interactive full automation (implies \fB\-\-yes\fR)
.TP
.BI \-\-offline " DISK"
Operate on an unmounted disk or image
.TP
.B \-\-suggest-next-command
Print the recommended follow-up command
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Success
.TP
.B 1
Fatal error
.TP
.B 2
Partial \- some operations succeeded, some failed
.TP
.B 3
Nothing to do (already in requested state)
.TP
.B 4
Refused due to a safety check
.TP
.B 5
User declined interactive confirmation
.TP
.B 6
Operation does not apply to this system
.TP
.B 7
Required tool or capability is missing
